ADMIN'S GUIDE Embedding on Website Builders Shopify Embedding on Shopify Easily bring your live stream to your audience on Shopify by embedding the LORA live stream player. To do so, begin by copying the embed code for your live stream from the LORA CMS Show Details page. There are two embed code formats available: one with the 'Watch Now' button, and one for direct display. Once you've obtained the embed code, follow these simple steps to embed the live stream player on your WordPress website: Log in to your Shopify account. Navigate to your desired page or create a new page. Within the “Content” section, click on “Show HTML”. Paste the code into the text editor. If you are using the live show direct display embed code, you can adjust the size of the video by editing the width and height attributes in the embed code. For short videos, you can adjust the size and position of the live stream player by clicking and dragging the code block on the page. Once you have pasted the embed code into the text editor click on “Save”. info To find out more about Shopify’s rich text editor, check out this documentation. ADMIN'S GUIDE Embedding on Website Builders Weebly Embedding on Weebly If you have a Weebly website and want to enhance it with live streams or short video playlists, you can easily do so with LORA. This guide will take you through the straightforward steps required to embed your live stream player or playlists on your Weebly site using the appropriate embed code. The steps are relevant for the following types of embed codes: Individual short videos Short video playlists Live show (both “Watch Now” button and Direct Display codes) Show lineup To embed your content onto Weebly: Log in to your Weebly account and go to the site editor. Click on the "Embed Code" element from the sidebar on the left-hand side. Drag and drop the "Embed Code" element to the location on your page where you want the code to appear. Click on the "Embed Code" element to open the editing window and click on “Edit Custom HTML”. Paste the code you want to embed into the text box provided. If you are using the live show direct display embed code, you can adjust the size of the video by editing the width and height attributes in the embed code. Click on the "Publish" button to save the changes to your page. Previous Embedding on Squarespace Next Embedding on Shopify

ADMIN'S GUIDE Embedding on Website Builders Wix On this page Embedding on Wix How to Embed LORA Live Shows on Wix​ LORA makes it easy to implement livestreams on your website with minimal technical knowledge required. By following a few simple steps, you can add your LORA live shows to your Wix website and provide your audience with an engaging and interactive experience. Here are the pre-requisites to embedding your live shows onto your Wix site: A Wix site with a Premium plan This is necessary because the “Custom Code” feature, which allows you to add external code to your site, is only available with a Premium plan. LORA Live Show embed code with “Watch Now” button The embed code will be generated after creating a live show. Due to restrictions by Wix, the Direct Display embed code option is not compatible on Wix. Once you have satisfied the prerequisites mentioned above, follow these steps to successfully embed your live show. To summarize, you will need to paste the embed code into your site and assign a button to open the live show player via the live show's URL. Add the Embed Code into your site​ On your LORA CMS, copy the “Watch Now“ embed code from the LORA CMS Show Details page. Your code should look something like this: <button id="YOUR_ELEMENT_ID">Watch live</button><script> var scriptElement = document.createElement("script"); scriptElement.src = "https://lora-sdk.belive.sg/player-widget/latest/player.min.js"; scriptElement.onload = function () { const player = window.BeLivePlayerWidget.initialize({ showId: "d1234a05-0bfa-123j4-baae-5d9da24089e5", triggerElement: document.getElementById("YOUR_ELEMENT_ID"), }); }; document.body.appendChild(scriptElement);</script> Login to your Wix Premium site and go to the editor for the site where you want to embed the livestream player. Click on the “+Add“ button in the left-hand menu, click “Embed Code“. Scroll down until you see the "Custom Code" option and click on it. Click on “Add Custom Code“ on the top-right corner of the window. Paste the embed code into the Code Snippet field. After pasting, delete the ‘button id’ tag from the code. Your code should now look like this: <script> var scriptElement = document.createElement("script"); scriptElement.src = "https://lora-sdk.belive.sg/player-widget/latest/player.min.js"; scriptElement.onload = function () { const player = window.BeLivePlayerWidget.initialize({ showId: "d1234a05-0bfa-123j4-baae-5d9da24089e5", triggerElement: document.getElementById("YOUR_ELEMENT_ID"), }); }; document.body.appendChild(scriptElement);</script> Select to place the code in the Body-Start or Body-End sections. You can also give the code a name for your reference, and select which page to add the code to. Click “Apply“. Add a button to open the live player​ In the Wix editor, select the page where you want to add the button. Click on the “+ Add“ button on the left-hand side of the editor. Select the "Button" option from the list of elements. Choose the style of the button you want to use from the menu of options that appear. Click and drag the button to the desired location on your page. Click on the button to select it, and then click on the link icon. In the menu that pops up, select “Web Address”. In the URL field, enter the URL of your live show player. This should be the Wix site URL of where your live show is embedded, followed by /?beliveShowId=”YOUR_SHOW_ID”. Replace “YOUR_SHOW_ID” with the Show ID of your live show, which can be copied from your CMS. Example: https://yourwixsite.com/events/?beliveShowId=d1234a05-0bfa-123j4-baae-5d9da24089e5 Click “Save” to apply the changes and add the button to your page. That's it! With these steps, you should now be able to easily embed a short video or playlist on your Wix website. ADMIN'S GUIDE Embedding on Website Builders Wordpress On this page Embedding on Wordpress Embedding Live Shows​ If you're using WordPress to host your website, you can easily embed our live stream player and bring your live stream to your audience. To get started, you'll need to copy the embed code from the LORA CMS Show Details page. You can find the embed code for your live stream in two formats: one with the 'Watch Now' button, and one for direct display. Once you've obtained the embed code, follow these simple steps to embed the live stream player on your WordPress website: Login to your WordPress dashboard and navigate to the page or post where you want to embed the live stream player. Switch to the text editor mode by clicking on the “Text” tab at the top-right corner of the editor. Paste the embed code into the desired location in the text editor. If you're using the direct display embed code, you can adjust the size of the player by editing the “width” and “height” attributes in the code. tip To ensure an optimal viewing experience, it is recommended to use a video size that has a 16:9 (portrait orientation) aspect ratio. Save the changes to the page or post, and then preview the page to see the live stream player in action. If you are using WPBakery, Gutenberg or Elementor page editor plug-ins, here's how to embed your live stream player on WordPress: Copy the embed code from the LORA CMS in the Show Details page. In WordPress, open the page where you want to embed the live stream player. If you're using WPBakery, click on the "+" icon to add a new element to the page. Then select the "Raw HTML" element and paste your embed code into the block. You can customize the block's settings as needed. If you're using Gutenberg, click on the "+" icon to add a new block to the page. Then select the "Custom HTML" block and paste your embed code into the block. You can preview the block in real-time and adjust its settings as needed. If you're using Elementor, drag the "HTML" widget from the list of available widgets onto your page. Then paste your embed code into the widget and customize it as needed. Save your changes and preview your page to ensure that the live stream player is working correctly. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Live Engagement Tools To create live shows with more impact and engage with viewers better, you can run engagement tools during live shows. When you run these tools, you will be able to view the results during the live show as well as in the analytics page after the live show ends. You can only run one live engagement tool at a time during the live show. Engagement tools that you can run are: Live Quiz Live Polling Live Announcement Live Rating Lucky Draw note If you are simulcasting the live show, viewers will be unable to interact with the engagement tool on the social media destination. They will have to directed to your embedded LORA live player to interact. Previous Simulcasting to Twitch Next Live Quiz

ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Live Announcement On this page Live Announcement Live announcements can be created to ensure your important messages are sent across to viewers even as they come in and out of your live show. It also ensures that your script is not interrupted with repetitive messages that could still be crucial for your viewers to know. A live announcement will appear as a scrolling text at the top of the screen. Creating a live announcement​ Live announcements can only be created during a live show. To create a live announcement, click on Interactivity and Announcement in the Admin Watch screen. Input title. This is for your own reference and viewers will not see the title of your live announcement Input text. This is the content of your live announcement. You can customise the text and appearance of your announcements. Live announcements will appear as a scrolling text banner at the top of your live shows and you can toggle to display it on or off at any time during the live show. You can customise the appearance of your live announcement.. Previous Live Polling Next Live Rating Creating a live announcement

ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Live Polling On this page Live Polling Live polls can help to increase interactions with your live viewers and also lets you discover their interests or expectations towards your products. You can start polling questions at any time during your live show, and restart the same questions to ensure you get the maximum number of responses during the live show. Create your polling questions on the CMS before the live show, and use them again and again across your live shows. Creating a live poll​ To create a live poll, click on Engagement Tools and Polling. Click on Create Polling, where you will create a set of questions and answers. Input poll title This is for your own reference to the set of questions and answers and will not be shown to viewers. Enter question and option answers Every question requires 2-4 options for answers. Starting a live poll​ During your live show, you can choose to start any poll questions, one at a time. Click on Interactivity in the Admin Watch screen and select Polling to view all your created polls. On the Admin Watch screen, you can view all polling questions and select which to start. To start a poll, click on the Play button. A timer will start so you can measure how long the question has been running for. When viewers answer the poll, you will be able to view the results instantly. You can choose to publish the results to the poll question after stopping the poll by clicking on the Stop button. Live poll archive​ After ending and saving the live show, the live poll analytics will be shown in the archives for you to revisit. You can export the polling results into a spreadsheet. Live Polling vs Live Quiz​ Live polling and live quizzes have several differences: Live Polling Live Quizzes Does not require you to select a correct answer Requires you to select which option should be the correct answer You can start or stop specific questions independently When you start a quiz, it will run through the entire course of questions and answers itself. Does not require duration configuration, but will require you to start and stop manually Requires duration configurations (i.e question duration, answer duration, interval duration) Previous Live Quiz Next Live Announcement Creating a live poll Starting a live poll Live poll archive Live Polling vs Live Quiz

ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Lucky Draw On this page Lucky draw Creating a lucky draw event allows you to manually or randomly select winners within your viewers. This is useful if you are hosting a giveaway or any event that requires drawing names from your viewers. Generally, each lucky draw event involves selecting viewers as winners based on filters or through manual selection. From each event, you can display the list of names selected (i.e the winner list) to all your viewers. Winners will see a pop up to input their email addresses so that they can be contacted by you. Creating a lucky draw event​ You can only create lucky draw events during the live show. Input title. This title is for your own reference only and will not be displayed to the viewers. Select filter. There are two filters you can choose from: Viewers who are currently online at the moment you are creating the lucky draw event Guest viewers (i.e viewers who are not signed in to your website) Click List. The candidate list will populate with names based on your selected filters. After your candidate list is populated, you can input the number of names to auto draw or you can manually select the names to add from the Candidate List into the Winner List. Once you are satisfied with the Winner List, click create. You will be brought back to the Admin Watch screen where you can view the results of the lucky draw event you created. To publish the results, click on View Results and Publish. the Winner List will be displayed to viewers. Winners will see a pop up to input their email address to be contacted as a winner. Viewers in the winner list will see the pop up requesting for email address. Lucky Draw Results​ After your live show has ended, you will be able to go to your live show’s archive to view the analytics as well as the results of the lucky draw events. To view the email addresses collected from the winners, export the lucky draw analytics sheet. note Lucky draw results and the corresponding email address responses will only be saved if you had published the winner list during the live show. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Live Rating On this page Live Rating You can gain feedback on your products or live show by creating a live rating sticker. It lets you understand how viewers perceive your products or live show through the representation of stars. A live rating sticker will appear on the side of the screen Creating a live rating​ Live rating stickers can only be created during the live show on the Admin Watch screen. To create a live rating sticker, click on Interactivity and Live Rating in the Admin Watch Screen. Input the Question. This is the question displayed in the rating sticker and it should be based on what you want viewers to rate. Select whether you want to feature a product or not. If you feature a product, the sticker will show an image of the selected product. You can only select products that you have added into your live show. Starting a live rating​ After you have created your live rating sticker, you can choose to start the live rating any time during the live show. To start a live rating, click on the Play button. A timer will start so you can measure how long the question has been running for. When viewers submit their live rating results, you will be able to view the results. You can choose to publish the results to the live rating sticker question after stopping the sticker by clicking on the Stop button. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Engagement Tools Live Quiz On this page Live Quiz Hosting live quizzes is an effective way to educate and entertain viewers. Generally, you can create sets of questions before the live show. You will be required to configure certain aspects of the quiz, such as the duration of appearance for questions, and whether you would like to accept email addresses. During the live show, you can then play any sets quizzes and let it run itself based on your configuration. You can choose to publish the winner list at the end of every quiz. Creating a live quiz​ To create a live quiz, click on Engagement Tools and Quizzes in the side navigation. Click on Create Quiz. When you create a quiz, you are creating a set of questions and answers with the respective configuration. Questions in a quiz will be played one after another automatically in the live show. Input quiz title This is for your own reference to the set of questions and answers and will not be shown to viewers. Enter question and option answers Every question requires 2-4 options for answers. You have to select which option is the correct answer. Configure durations On the right side of the quiz creation page, you can configure the question duration, answer duration and interval duration respectively. Question Duration: Determines the amount of time viewers get to answer a question. Answer Duration: Determines the amount of screen time for the answers of each question. Interval Duration: Determines the amount of time in between a question and its answer, and between an answer and the next question. You can choose to request for email addresses by viewers if you require a method to contact winners. Take note that currently, viewers have the option to join the quiz without submitting an email address. note The pop-up to input email addresses will appear for the same duration set as the Interval Duration. The pop-up will appear before the quiz starts, but a button to submit email address will always be available on the right side during the course of the quiz if the viewer has never submitted an email address before. Starting a live quiz​ During a live show, click on Interactivity and Live Quizzes to see a list of all your created quizzes. When you’re ready to start a quiz, click on the Play button. You will be asked to review all the questions, answers and configurations before starting it. Once you click on Start, you will have a five-second buffer where you can still cancel the quiz. Once the five seconds are up your quiz will run itself, unless you force end it which will result in the cutting the quiz short. To force end the quiz, hover over the Ongoing button and you can click End. Quizzes can still be restarted after ending. How to moderate a live quiz​ Using the host app​ If your live show was started using the host app, you will be able to see timer cues in the host app that lets you know when the next question and answer will appear. This way, the host knows how long to interact with the viewers in between questions and answers. Using Admin Watch screen​ If your live show was started using an External Broadcasting source, you can use a separate device to watch the live quiz from the viewer’s point of view. Alternatively, the Admin Watch screen will also display the timer cues in the overlay box. On the Admin Watch screen, the overlay box contains the cues for live quiz. The winner list​ After each live quiz ends, you will be able to see the winner list. A View Winners button will be displayed after the live quiz ends and you can see a list of winners. The Winner List shows the Top 50 participants, ranked according to score. 1 correct answer = 1 score. You can choose to publish the winner list. note If there are more than one participants with the same score, these participants with the same score will be listed in order of who started answering the quiz earliest. Live Quiz Archive​ Once your live show ends, you will be able to review the results of the live quiz again in the Archive Analytics. You can export the analytics report of the live quiz to view the email address of the participants, if you had enabled this. Live Quiz vs Live Polling​ Live polling and live quizzes have several differences: Live Polling Live Quizzes Does not require you to select a correct answer Requires you to select which option should be the correct answer You can start or stop specific questions independently When you start a quiz, it will run through the entire course of questions and answers itself. Does not require duration configuration, but will require you to start and stop manually Requires duration configurations (i.e question duration, answer duration, interval duration) Previous Live Engagement Tools Next Live Polling Creating a live quiz Starting a live quiz How to moderate a live quiz Using the host app Using Admin Watch screen The winner list Live Quiz Archive Live Quiz vs Live Polling

ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Using Host Apps On this page Using Host App LORA Host App The LORA host app is needed for you to start your live shows. It uses the device’s camera for the video feed. tip If you want to use an external camera instead of your mobile phone camera, you can use an External Broadcasting Software to connect an external camera. Test Network​ Before going live, it is recommended to test your network to avoid disruptions. To test your network with the host app, tap on Test Network on the pre-live screen, which will redirect you to fast.com The recommended Upload and Download speed is at least 10 Mbp. Start Live on LORA Host App​ Log in Your host will have to log into the host app. Create an account for your host on the Dashboard and pass them the Email and Password credentials. Select the live show The host will be able to see the live show assigned to them. Start Live Once you are ready to go live, tap on Start Live. Moderating on LORA Host App.​ We recommend sticking your moderating activity to only one platform (i.e either CMS Dashboard or Host App). While the host is live, below are the following actions they can take with the Host app: Read and send live chat messages Pin up to three products Pin a comment Toggle beauty filter Flip camera Sort products Ending Live Show​ To end your live show, click on the Close button on the top right hand corner of the live screen. Select to save your live show or not. ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Using External Broadcasting Softwares On this page Using External Broadcasting Softwares External Broadcasting Softwares (EBS) If you are using an external broadcasting software (e.g OBS, Streamlabs, etc), you will need a slightly different process to go live with LORA. You will not need to start your live with the Host App. Going Live With EBS​ When creating your Live Show, toggle ON the External Broadcasting Software option. When you are ready to go live, click on Start Show Copy the RTMP URL and Stream Key note The RTMP URL and Stream Key changes every time you click on Start Show. Be sure to copy the latest values. Paste the RTMP URL and Stream Key into your EBS settings Start Streaming on your EBS Click Start on LORA Dashboard You should be directed to your Admin Watch page right away. You will see a small pop up at the bottom right of your screen. You can hide the pop up, and go about the rest of your show as per normal. Ending Live With EBS​ When you are ready to end your live show: Click on End Live in the small pop up window or on the button below your live video feed in the Admin Watch page. ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Moderating on Admin Dashboard On this page Moderating on Admin Watch Page You can send chat messages as an admin and manage products from the Dashboard while a live show is ongoing. To go to the Admin Watch page, go to the main Live Show listing page. A show that is currently live would have LIVE as its status. Click on View. Moderating Chat​ On the Chat tab in the Admin Watch page, you can send and read chat messages sent by viewers. Other actions you can take: Pin Comment You can pin one comment at a time by clicking on the sender's name and clicking Pin. A pinned comment will stick to the top of the live chat until it is unpinned. Reply To reply viewer's messages directly, you can click on their name in the chat message and click Reply. All viewers will be able to see your reply. Mute To unmute a disruptive viewer, you can click on their name and click Mute. The viewer will be informed that they have been muted and will be unable to send chat messages. Moderating Products​ On the Products tab, you can manage your selection of products for the live show. Some actions you can take: Pin products You can pin up to three products onto the live show screen. When clicked on the pinned products, the viewer will be directed to the product's URL. Add/Remove products You can select more products to add into the live show by clicking on the + icon in the Products Tab. You can click on the - icon next to the product to remove a product from the live show. This will not delete your product from your Dashboard CMS. Sort products You can click and drag each product in the listing to reorder your listing. Product tagging You can change your product tags by clicking on the dropdown menu of each product. Currently, two admin accounts are able to moderate on the same live show at the same time. However, it is recommended to assign specific actions to specific admins, to avoid clashing of activity. note Your viewers will be able to see the changes reflected after refreshing the live show player by closing and opening the product catalogue. ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Simulcasting to Social Platforms Simulcasting to Social Platforms Simulcast, or multi-streaming, is pushing your live show to social media platforms such as YouTube or Facebook. This will allow you to extend your reach and ensure your live shows are still being watched by your audience on your social media platforms. tip When you simulcast, viewers on social media platforms will not be able to interact with Live Engagement Tools. You need to direct viewers to where your LORA live player is embedded. Below are articles breaking down the steps to simulcast to individual social media platforms: Simulcasting to YouTube Simulcasting to Facebook Simulcasting to Twitch You are able to simulcast to other platforms as well, if you have access to the RTMP URL and Stream Key. Take note that this might involve the use of external tools and resources, especially for TikTok and Instagram. Previous Using Host App Next Simulcasting to YouTube

ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Simulcasting to Social Platforms Simulcasting to Facebook On this page Simulcasting to Facebook Simulcast to Facebook:​ Navigate to the Facebook page or profile where you would like to live stream to. In the Create area, click on Live Video and then select Go Live. You will be directed to Facebook’s live producer portal. Under Select a video source, ensure that Streaming Software is selected. You will be able to find the Stream Key. Click on Advanced Settings dropdown to reveal the Server URL. You can configure other settings for your stream on Facebook which will not affect your live show where the LORA player is embedded. For more details on these settings, check out Facebook’s documentation. On the LORA CMS, create your live show and fill in the details in the basic tab. Next, click on the advanced tab and scroll down to the Simulcast section. You will be able to see the following: Click on the Facebook button. Input the Channel Name. This can be your Facebook profile or page name. It is for your own reference only to help you identify which channel you are simulcasting to. Copy and paste the Stream URL and Stream Key from Facebook (as mentioned in Step 2) into the respective fields. Click Add. You can add more than one YouTube channels to simulcast by repeating the steps above. Whenever you’re ready, go live as per normal from LORA. Once you are Live, you will start to receive the live video and audio on Facebook. Confirm that the video and audio are correct and synchronised. Click Go Live on Facebook. Once you’re live on Facebook, a live video post is created and your Facebook followers will be notified that you are live. When you’re ready to end, end the live stream on Facebook first by clicking on End live video in the lower-left corner of the Producer portal. Then, end the live show from LORA. ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Simulcasting to Social Platforms Simulcasting to Twitch On this page Simulcasting to Twitch Simulcast to Twitch:​ On Twitch, sign in and navigate to the main menu and go to Creator Dashboard. From there, open the hamburger menu on the left and click on Settings > Stream. You will be able to find your stream key here. Copy the stream key. Copy the RTMP URL for your simulcast. You can see the list of RTMP URLs you are closest to here: https://stream.twitch.tv/ingests/ On the LORA CMS, create your live show and fill in the details in the basic tab. Next, click on the advanced tab and scroll down to the Simulcast section. You will be able to see the following: Click on the Twitch button. Input the Channel Name. This can be your Twitch username. It is for your own reference only to help you identify which channel you are simulcasting to. Copy and paste the Stream URL and Stream Key from Twitch (as mentioned in Step 2 and 3) into the respective fields. You will need to paste the Stream Key in twice – first over the {stream key} portion of the RTMP URL, then in the Stream Key field itself. Click Add. You can add more than one Twitch channels to simulcast by repeating the steps above. Whenever you’re ready, go live as per normal from LORA. It will automatically simulcast to Twitch. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Host and Admin Accounts On this page Host and Admin Accounts Creating Admin Accounts​ After onboarding, you should have received your LORA Dashboard email and password. You can change you password on the log in screen. If you require more admin accounts, please contact your LORA sales representative. note Only one device can be logged into a LORA account at the same time Creating Host Accounts​ Host accounts can be created for your live show hosts or KOLs. These accounts are created through the dashboard, but used to sign into the host app. This is to ensure that your external influencers hosting the live shows will not see any sensitive information you might have on the dashboard tip Admin accounts can be used to log into the host app, but Host accounts cannot be used to log into the dashboard. To create a host account: Under the side navigation, go to Account Click on Users Management Click on Add User Input their Display Name, Email, and Password Provide the Email and Password credentials to your host to log into the host app. If they have forgotten the password, you can set a new password for the host in the Users Management screen of the Dashboard. ADMIN'S GUIDE Going Live Simulcasting to Social Platforms Simulcasting to YouTube On this page Simulcasting to YouTube Simulcast to YouTube:​ Log into your YouTube account, click the Create button at the top and click Go live. You will then see the following screen: Enter your event’s Title and select your desired Privacy setting for YouTube. Note that this will not impact the privacy of your stream embedded with the LORA video player. After configuring the above details as desired, click Create Stream. You will see the following screen: This is where your stream will come in after you go live from LORA and where you will push the stream live to YouTube. You can click on Edit at the top to edit your event details. In the bottom left corner is where you will be able to get the RTMP URL and Stream Key. Click on the eye icon to unhide the stream key. Each of these will need to be copied into your LORA CMS. note Do not share your Stream Key anywhere else! On the LORA CMS, create your live show and fill in the details in the basic tab. Next, click on the advanced tab and scroll down to the Simulcast section. You will be able to see the following: Click on the YouTube button. Input the Channel Name. This name is for your own reference only to help you identify which channel you are simulcasting to. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Create Live Shows (Advanced) On this page Create Live Shows (Advanced) Advanced Live Show Settings​ In the Advanced tab of your live show creation page, you can configure more settings of the live show. Chat Settings​ Allow guest to chat: Guest viewers refers to viewers who are not signed into your website, if you have sign-in authentication on your website. If you toggle this ON: Viewers who are not signed in are able to chat normally. They will be assigned a random unique name (e.g Shopper 2123) If you toggle this OFF: When viewers who are not signed in attempt to send a chat message, your Sign-in Prompt will activated. For this to happen, you need to handle the callback. Allow guest to change display name: As mentioned above, guest viewers will be assigned a random unique name when they send messages in chat. If you toggle this ON: Guest viewers can change their display name any time during the show. They can change this multiple times. If you toggle this OFF: Guest viewers will remain with their assigned random unique name when chatting throughout the live show. info What about signed-in viewers? If your viewers are signed into your website, their account name will be used as display name in chat and they will not be able to change their display names. Admin Chat Display name: By default, when the admin sends chat messages through the Admin Watch page, the display name will be the admin’s account username. You can choose to input a new display name for the live show. The new name will not be automatically brought over to the next live show. Branding​ For each live show, you can choose to add a logo to use as a watermark in your live shows. This logo will appear on the top right corner of the live show and it will not be automatically brought over to the next live show. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Create Live Shows (Basic) On this page Create Live Shows (Basic) To create a live show, click on Show and then Live Show in the side navigation. Click on the Create Show button to start creating a live show. In the Live Show Creation screen, you will see two sections available. Basic is where you will set up the fundamental aspects of your live show, while Advanced is where you can configure more specific settings. Example of Create Show Show Title The show title is used for your own internal reference on the Dashboard and Host app. It will not be shown to viewers. note If you are using external broadcasting sources (such as OBS or Streamlabs, you can follow this guide on how to start the live show.) Pre-stream Cover and Placeholder Cover If you have embedded your show onto your website but the show has yet to start, viewers will see the Pre-stream cover image. tip Use the Pre-stream cover image as a banner to inform your viewers when the live show will start, or the topic of your live show. The placeholder cover image will be shown onto your website in the event that your show has already been embedded but not saved as a recorded show for website visitors to watch. Select Host Select the host who will be hosting the live show. When the host is selected, they will be able to see the live show assigned to them in the host app. Hosts will only see live shows that are assigned to them. You can select admins as the host as well. If you are running a live show with an External Broadcasting Software, you will not have to select a host. Select Product (optional) When you click on the field, you will be able to view and select the products that you have created. You can remove or select more products into the live show even during the live show itself. note If no products are selected for the live show, the Product button in the live show will be hidden from viewers until you add a product. Add Voucher (optional) Vouchers are placed in your live show catalogue. If you have an active voucher code on your website, you can use the same code here so that your viewers can copy the code and paste into your website checkout page. Voucher codes are placed in the product catalogue of the live show. Select Theme By default, you can use the Standard Theme. You can also create a theme to apply to your live show. Standard Player Theme appearance (i.e the default appearance) Standard Live Screen Theme appearance (i.e the default appearance) After you created the live show, you will be able to see the generated embed code. FAQ​ Can two shows go live at the same time? One host can only start one live show at a time. However, you can have multiple hosts going live at the same time from different host accounts. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Embedding Live Shows On this page Embedding Live Shows There are two choices in embedding live shows: Embedding with Watch Now button, or displaying the live show directly. While the method of embedding both choices is the same, the outputs are different. 1. Embedding with Watch Now button.​ When you use this embed code onto your landing page, viewers will see a Watch Now button. If your live show has started, clicking on the Watch Now button will open the live show player with the chat and products section. If your live show has ended and was saved, viewers will be able to watch the recording as well. If your live show has not started yet, it will show the pre-stream cover image upon clicking the Watch Now button. If your live show has ended but the recording was not saved, the placeholder image will be shown. How the live player looks like with just the pre-stream cover image or placeholder image. If your live show has been deleted but is still embedded on your landing page, viewers will see the default placeholder image upon clicking the Watch Now button. 2. Embedding Directly with no Watch Now button.​ When you use this embed code on your landing page, what the viewer will see in the different situations is the same as described above. However, the viewers will not have to click a Watch Now button to open the player. Instead, the live show player will be displayed directly on your landing page. The desktop web view will take on the UI style of the mobile web view. How To Embed Live Shows: After creating a live show, you will be able to see an embed code generated at the bottom of your Live Show Details page. Copy the embed code. info Each live show will have its own embed code. If you want to use only one embed code for multiple live shows, you can create Show Lineups. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Embedding Live Shows Show Lineups On this page Show Lineups Purpose of Show Lineups​ When you create a new live show, you will have to replace the previous show’s embed code with a new one if you are using the same landing page or entry point. A show lineup will be able to reduce your effort needed in replacing embed codes. By grouping several live shows into one lineup, a lineup embed code will be generated. This lineup embed code can be used such that when you switch from one show to the next, you will not need to change embed codes. How To Create A Show Lineup​ A typical use case of using a show lineup is to organise your shows based on entry points. For example, you can create a lineup for shows that will appear in the main real estate of your landing page, and another lineup for shows that will appear in a different webpage. To create a show lineup: Create your live shows as per normal. Click on the Show Lineups in the Live Show listing page. Click on Create Lineup Give the lineup a title for your own reference (e.g Landing Page shows). Viewers will not see this title. Select the shows that you have created to add into the lineup and sort in order of appearance. Select the Featured Show. This is selecting what the viewers should see if there is no ongoing live show from the lineup. By default, if no live shows from the lineup has started at all, viewers will see the pre-stream cover image of the first live show. Save the lineup. A lineup embed code will be generated. Copy the embed code and paste it onto the HTML script of your landing page. On the viewer’s side, watching a show from a lineup is no different from watching a show not in a lineup. You can start a live show from a lineup as per normal. Order Of Shows In A Lineup​ The order in which your live show is sorted is the order which the Featured Show will come into play. However, you are not restricted to starting live shows in the exact same order. note Show Lineups do not support concurrent live streaming. If a second live show in a lineup is started by a different host, viewers will not be able to enter the first live show anymore. ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Products On this page Products Creating Products​ You can create products manually on the Dashboard to use it in Live and Video Shows, or Short Videos. tip You can also bulk upload products using an excel sheet. To create a product: Go to Products under the side navigation Click on Create Product Input the following information: Product name Product Image Product Price (optional) Discount Value % (optional) This is the discount percentage to make your products appear attractive to purchase by viewers Promotional Price (optional) This is the price after discount values Product SKU (optional) You will only need to input this in if you are using Cart Integration for your live shows. This refers to the SKU or Product ID that is used for the product in your e-commerce system (e.g Shopify, Magento, custom, etc.) Product Link This is the URL that viewers will be directed to if they click on the products in the live show. Most of the time, this will be the product page on your website. Product Tagging Product tags are labels that will be displayed on your product during the live show. These can help to bring more attention or urgency to purchasing your products. You can change these tags during the live show. Example of Product Tags on Live Show catalogue Product currency can be set under Settings. Take note that any change in currency will be reflected in all shows with products. Once you have created your products, you can select to use your products in Live Show Creation. Previous Host and Admin Accounts Next Bulk Upload Creating Products

ADMIN'S GUIDE Embedding on Website Builders Squarespace On this page Embedding on Squarespace How to Embed Live Shows and Short Videos on Squarespace:​ You can easily embed your live stream player using the provided embed code from the LORA CMS. This guide will walk you through the simple steps to embed your live stream player or short video playlists into your Squarespace website using the appropriate embed code. The steps are applicable for the following embed codes: Individual short videos Short video playlists Live show (both “Watch Now” button and Direct Display codes) To embed your content onto Squarespace: Log in to your Squarespace account and go to the page where you want to embed the live stream player. Click on the “+ Add Block” button to add a new block to the page and select 'Code' from the list of options. A new code block will appear on the page. Double click the block to open the code editor. Copy your embed code from the LORA CMS. Paste the embed code into the code block editor. If you are using the live show direct display embed code, you can adjust the size of the video by editing the width and height attributes in the embed code. For short videos, you can adjust the size and position of the live stream player by clicking and dragging the code block on the page. Once you have pasted the embed code into the code block editor, hover over “Done” and click “Save” to publish your changes. note Squarespace does not allow you to preview your embedded codes. You will have to publish and view the page as a visitor by logging out of your site and visiting it, or opening it in an incognito window. For more information on embedding in Squarespace, visit their help center. Previous Embedding on Wix Next Embedding on Weebly How to Embed Live Shows and Short Videos on Squarespace:

ADMIN'S GUIDE Live Shows Themes On this page Themes Creating Themes​ Themes allow you to customise your live video player to suit to your branding or special events. There are two components to themes: Live Player and Live Screen. By default, your live show’s theme will be the standard BeLive player and generic button icons. To create a Theme, click on Themes in the side navigator and then Create Themes. Give your theme a Name. The Theme Name just for your own reference in the Dashboard, and not seen by viewers. Player Theme​ The Player refers to the live video seek bar and control buttons that viewers will see on the recorded live show. You can customise the overlay colour and the player button colour note Viewers will not see the player seek bar during the live show. But after the live show ends and the recorded live stream is accessible for viewers to watch, the seek bar and control buttons will be visible. Example of a customised Theme Player Live Screen Theme​ The Live Screen refers to the interactive layer of the live show. You can customise the Accent colour, Floating Hearts colour and Live label colour. You can also upload your own Likes, Shop, Share and Cart button. Example of a customised Live Screen note The Cart button will only be shown if your live show has cart integration. You can reuse your themes across multiple live shows. If you edit a theme, the changes will be reflected on the recorded live shows with that theme. Once you have created a theme, you can select to use your new themes in Live Show Creation. ADMIN'S GUIDE Short Videos Creating Playlists On this page Creating Playlists Creating playlists allow you to group and embed your short videos into layouts. You can add one short video into multiple playlists, and you can have an unlimited number of short videos in one playlist. How To Create Playlists​ To create a playlist, click on Short Video in the side navigation. You will be brought to the short video gallery where you will be able to see the Short Video and Playlist tabs. Click on the Playlist tab. This is where your playlists will be listed. Click on Create Playlist on the bottom right. Enter the name of your playlist (this is for reference only and will not be visible to viewers). Adding Short Videos to Playlists​ There are two ways to add short videos into your playlist. Within the Playlist tab In the Playlist tab, click on the playlist you would like to add created short videos to. Click on Add Video on the right side. This will open a window of your created short videos that you can add into your playlist. Select your short videos and click Add. During short video creation When you are creating your short video, click on the Add to Playlist field. You can select which playlist(s) to add the short video to. Now that you have a playlist of videos, you can embed your playlist into layouts. ADMIN'S GUIDE Short Videos Creating Short Videos & Adding Interactive Overlays On this page Creating Short Videos & Adding Interactive Overlays To create a short video, click on Short Video in the side navigation. You will be brought to the short video gallery where you will be able to see the Short Video and Playlist tabs. Click on the Create Video button on the bottom right to open the video creation window. How To Create Short Videos​ Upload your short video Short videos have to be from 3 to 60 seconds long, and no bigger than 100MB. While waiting for your video to upload, you can input the other fields. Input title This title can be seen from the viewer side. You can change this again after saving. Add to playlist If you have already created a playlist you can select at least one playlist to add the short video into. You can also leave this field empty and add the short video into a playlist later. Select overlay There are four options to choose from: None (i.e no overlay), Shop CTA, Polling, and Q&A. Short Video Overlays​ Shop CTA: Shop CTA allows you to overlay your products in your CMS over your Short Video. When viewers click on the products in your short video, they will be directed to the product URL. Shop CTA overlay on the Viewer's side info 👀 Coming Soon: You will be able to integrate short video products with your e-commerce cart. Stay tuned! Polling: Polling allows you to add a poll question and up to four options over your short video. Viewers will be able to see the updated results after selecting an option. Polling overlay on Viewer's side Q&A: Q&A allows you to ask an open-ended and viewers can submit their answers. You can also choose to have a follow-up field for your viewers to answer. Q&A overlay on Viewer's side Follow-up question on Viewer's side After creating your Short Video, you can embed it individually or add it into a playlist. ADMIN'S GUIDE Short Videos Shopify Cart Integration On this page Shopify Cart Integration If you are embedding your live shows on Shopify, you can enable cart integration for a seamless viewing and buying experience. Your audience will be able to accomplish these within the short video or playlist: View product details Select the product variation Add to cart Get redirected straight from cart to your check-out page There are three components to accomplishing this: Creating LORA Products with SKU Creating your short video Embedding your short video and playlists into Shopify Creating LORA Products with SKU​ For cart integration within short videos to work, you will need to copy the unique product identifier from your Shopify dashboard to your LORA CMS Product details. From your Shopify dashboard, go in the details page of your product. Copy the string of numbers in the browser URL. This will be known as the SKU. From the same page, copy the URL in the search engine listing. This is the Product URL. Create the product in your LORA CMS. Input the name, image and price accordingly. In the Stock Keeping Unit (SKU) field, paste the SKU value which you copied in Step 1. In the ‘Product Link’ field, paste the Product URL which you copied in Step 2. Save your product and repeat for all products which you would like to add for a cart integrated short video. Creating your short video​ Now that your products have SKU fields that match your Shopify admin product details, you can now create your cart integrated short videos and playlists. Create your short video in the LORA CMS. Upload your video, input your video title, and select the Shop CTA overlay. Select your desired Shop CTA and desired text colour. Toggle on ‘Cart Integration’ Select the products you would like to add in. note Products with no SKU inputted can still be added into the short video. Products with no SKU will direct viewers to the product URL instead of opening the product details screen within the short video. You can select your desired playlist to add the short video into as well. A playlist can be made up of a mix of cart integrated and non-cart integrated short videos. Playlists and short videos embedded within the same Shopify site will share the same cart. Embedding your short video and playlists into Shopify​ Now that your short videos and playlists are ready, you can easily embed them into your Shopify pages. On your Shopify dashboard, navigate to your desired page or create a new page Within the “Content” section, click on “Show HTML”. Paste your individual short video or playlist embed code into the text editor. info Find out where to find your short video embed codes in this article. Once you have pasted the embed code into the HTML editor click on “Save”. To view your short videos or playlists, you will need to preview the page or save it and view as a visitor to your page. Now that you have cart integration with short videos enabled, you can now view your conversion analytics for each individual short video. To do that, go to your Short Video gallery in your LORA CMS. Click on the click on the Action icon and click ‘Analytics’. DEVELOPER'S GUIDE Integrate the player Advanced On this page Advanced usage Set user credential​ This user information are for setting display info for the live chat feature. note This function is optional, When not specify, we will generate random user informations. Simply call setUser function to do this player.setUser({ id: "123", displayName: "ABC",}); Registers event listeners​ Register any event listeners from the PlayerEventType player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.READY, () => { console.log("Player Widget READY");});player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.MINIMIZED, () => { console.log("Player Widget MINIMIZED");});player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.UNMINIMIZED, () => { console.log("Player Widget UNMINIMIZED");});player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.CLOSE, () => { console.log("Player Widget CLOSE");}); Remove registered event listeners​ Remove any registered listener from the PlayerEventType function onPlayerReady() { console.log("Player Widget Ready");}// Register the listenerplayer.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.READY, onPlayerReady);// Remove the listenerplayer.off(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.READY, onPlayerReady); Remove all event listeners​ player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.READY, () => { console.log("Player Widget ready");});player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.CLOSE, () => { console.log("Player Widget was closed");});// Remove all listeners aboveplayer.removeAllListeners(); Not allow guest to chat​ When creating a show, navigate to Advanced tab and switch off the Allow guest to chat toggle button Registers an event listener for AUTHENTICATION player.on(BeLivePlayerWidget.PlayerEventType.AUTHENTICATION, () => { // you logic for authentication}); In-app Browser​ Android​ Maintain Default WebView Cache Settings in Android Apps This guide highlights the importance of keeping the default WebView cache settings in Android applications to ensure a consistent and efficient user experience. We recommend not enabling the LOAD_CACHE_ELSE_NETWORK setting found in the Android WebView WebSettings class, as it may cause the display of outdated content. Reasons to Avoid LOAD_CACHE_ELSE_NETWORK: Stale content: Prioritizing cached content can lead to users viewing outdated information. Efficient data usage: Unnecessarily storing web content may result in wasteful data usage. Inconsistent user experience: Relying on cached content can cause inconsistencies between devices and sessions. Conclusion: To provide a reliable browsing experience, maintain the default WebView cache settings in Android applications and avoid enabling the LOAD_CACHE_ELSE_NETWORK setting I have embedded the LORA show script in Android WebView but when the viewers click on the “Product URL” while watching a live or recorded show, it doesn't open in a new tab or window. How can I achieve this behavior? To achieve this behavior, additional configurations are required. Please refer to the Kotlin code snippet as shown below. javaScriptEnabled = truewebViewClient = default implsetSupportMultipleWindows(true)webChromeClient = custom impl// This SupportMultipleWindows setting will allow the webview to open a new window when needed// (such as links with target=”_blank” attribute)// When this setting is true, the onCreateWindow method will be called in a WebChromeClient object : WebChromeClient() { override fun onCreateWindow( view: WebView?, isDialog: Boolean, isUserGesture: Boolean, resultMsg: Message? ): Boolean { val newWebView = WebView(context) // Make sure to setup this new webview first setupWebView(newWebView) val transport = resultMsg?.obj as WebViewTransport transport.webView = newWebView resultMsg.sendToTarget() // Open a new dialog to see the content of this web view openUrlInNewWindow(newWebView) return true } } iOS​ One of the most commonly seen issues is when viewers are watching the live show via iOS WebView, the show automatically enters into a fullscreen mode.
